"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228721","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-03-24","<p>The fielding of GB football teams at future Olympic Games is a matter for the national football authorities and the British Olympic Association.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2015-03-24T15:08:48.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228721/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228721/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-03-19","Olympic Games: Brazil","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have been involved in discussions to field a women's football team at the 2016 Olympic Games; and whether they have the support of the British Olympic Association to field a women's football team.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL5903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228722","Cabinet Office","false","2015-03-26","<p><em>It has not proved possible to respond to this question in the time available before Prorogation. Ministers will correspond directly with the Member.</em></p>",,"Lord Wallace of Saltaire",,"2015-03-26T17:02:32.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228722/answer","Biography information for Lord Wallace of Saltaire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228722/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-03-19","Public Sector: Disclosure of Information","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are conducting any reviews to examine any unintended consequences of the drive to create greater transparency in the public sector.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL5904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228723","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-03-25","<p /> <p>There is no requirement for journalists to identify themselves as such when requesting information from a public authority under the Freedom of Information Act 2000. Therefore we hold no reliable data as to what proportion of requests they are responsible for.</p><p> </p><p>In 2012 the Ministry of Justice commissioned a costing exercise, <em>‘Strand 3- Investigative Study to inform the FOIA (2000) post-legislative review’</em>, which concluded that in central government the average cost of handling a request for information was £184. It concluded that for central government the cost of dealing with FOI requests in 2011 was £8,5m.</p><p> </p><p>For non-central public authorities the study concluded that the average cost of handling a request for information was £164, however, there is no data as to how many requests are received by these, so a total cost has not been estimated.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-03-25T14:13:14.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228723/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228723/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-03-19","Freedom of Information","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the proportion of requests under freedom of information legislation which originate from journalists as opposed to members of the public since that legislation was enacted; and what assessment they have made of the cost to the public purse of the freedom of information scheme to date.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL5905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228724","Department for Transport","false","2015-03-25","<p>The Highways Agency published a litter strategy in April 2014 and this highlights that since April 2011 the amount of litter on the strategic road network has reduced by approximately 25%.</p><p> </p><p>The Highways Agency continues to work with relevant stakeholders on litter issues, including encouraging commercial vehicle operators to ensure their vehicles do not spill litter or debris. This includes working closely with the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (DEFRA) and Keep Britain Tidy to raise public awareness of the dangers and costs of litter.</p><p> </p><p>The Agency also undertakes campaigns to encourage motorists to take their litter home making use of social media channels and roadside variable message signs to remind drivers to dispose of their litter responsibly.</p><p> </p><p>DEFRA also plays an active role in reducing litter and, as you may know, provides funding to Keep Britain Tidy. This organisation is well established and undertakes a range of activities, including educational campaigns in respect of the impacts that litter can cause to the environment.</p><p> </p><p>In respect to local highway authority roads, the Department for Transport does not hold data in respect of litter on the local road network, as litter clearance is a matter for the relevant local authority.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Kramer",,"2015-03-25T13:40:34.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228724/answer","Biography information for Baroness Kramer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228724/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-03-19","Roads: Litter","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what evidence they are aware of regarding whether rubbish on the sides of roads in England has increased or decreased over the current Parliament, and what that evidence shows.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL5906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228725","Department of Health","false","2015-03-26","<p>The effect of the Ebola outbreak on Universal Health Coverage will be discussed at the next Commonwealth Health Ministers Meeting in May. Supporting countries to strengthen their health systems remains a top priority for the Government’s health work in West Africa and beyond.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has met with the Commonwealth Foundation to discuss how civil society in Sierra Leone can be supported in tackling the Ebola crisis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Ebola outbreak has further demonstrated the importance of supporting countries to implement the International Health Regulations core capacities in order to detect and respond to outbreaks quickly. The Government is keen to accelerate international efforts to this end, working closely with the World Health Organization and through partnerships such as the Global Health Security Agenda. The Government sees the Commonwealth Health Ministers Meeting as an opportunity for the Commonwealth Secretariat to raise awareness of the importance of health system strengthening in the Commonwealth.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government will work with the Government of Sierra Leone and partners to seek a legacy of effective systems and structures that will contribute to improved future service delivery and infrastructure. This will ensure that should Sierra Leone be faced with a subsequent outbreak of Ebola or other disease, it is able to respond effectively.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL5908 ; HL5909","2015-03-26T13:02:44.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228725/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228725/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-03-19","Commonwealth","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will raise the issue of the ebola outbreak and the requirement for health system strengthening in the Commonwealth at the next meeting of Commonwealth Health Ministers.","false","Biography information for Lord Boateng",,"Lord Boateng","HL5907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228726","Department of Health","false","2015-03-26","<p>The effect of the Ebola outbreak on Universal Health Coverage will be discussed at the next Commonwealth Health Ministers Meeting in May. Supporting countries to strengthen their health systems remains a top priority for the Government’s health work in West Africa and beyond.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has met with the Commonwealth Foundation to discuss how civil society in Sierra Leone can be supported in tackling the Ebola crisis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Ebola outbreak has further demonstrated the importance of supporting countries to implement the International Health Regulations core capacities in order to detect and respond to outbreaks quickly. The Government is keen to accelerate international efforts to this end, working closely with the World Health Organization and through partnerships such as the Global Health Security Agenda. The Government sees the Commonwealth Health Ministers Meeting as an opportunity for the Commonwealth Secretariat to raise awareness of the importance of health system strengthening in the Commonwealth.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government will work with the Government of Sierra Leone and partners to seek a legacy of effective systems and structures that will contribute to improved future service delivery and infrastructure. This will ensure that should Sierra Leone be faced with a subsequent outbreak of Ebola or other disease, it is able to respond effectively.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL5907 ; HL5909","2015-03-26T13:02:45.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228726/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228726/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-03-19","Commonwealth","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have met the Commonwealth Secretariat, or other institutions of the Commonwealth, to discuss health system strengthening as a response to the outbreak of ebola in Sierra Leone.","false","Biography information for Lord Boateng",,"Lord Boateng","HL5908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228727","Department of Health","false","2015-03-26","<p>The effect of the Ebola outbreak on Universal Health Coverage will be discussed at the next Commonwealth Health Ministers Meeting in May. Supporting countries to strengthen their health systems remains a top priority for the Government’s health work in West Africa and beyond.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has met with the Commonwealth Foundation to discuss how civil society in Sierra Leone can be supported in tackling the Ebola crisis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Ebola outbreak has further demonstrated the importance of supporting countries to implement the International Health Regulations core capacities in order to detect and respond to outbreaks quickly. The Government is keen to accelerate international efforts to this end, working closely with the World Health Organization and through partnerships such as the Global Health Security Agenda. The Government sees the Commonwealth Health Ministers Meeting as an opportunity for the Commonwealth Secretariat to raise awareness of the importance of health system strengthening in the Commonwealth.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government will work with the Government of Sierra Leone and partners to seek a legacy of effective systems and structures that will contribute to improved future service delivery and infrastructure. This will ensure that should Sierra Leone be faced with a subsequent outbreak of Ebola or other disease, it is able to respond effectively.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL5907 ; HL5908","2015-03-26T13:02:45.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228727/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228727/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-03-19","Commonwealth","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the role of the Commonwealth and its organisations in capacity-building in Commonwealth Ministries of Health and Parliaments, in the light of lessons learnt from the experience of Sierra Leone and the outbreak of ebola there.","false","Biography information for Lord Boateng",,"Lord Boateng","HL5909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228728","Department of Health","false","2015-03-25","<p>NHS England has responsibility for the commissioning of specialised services and is currently consulting on changes to the principles and processes by which it makes decisions on prioritising investment in specialised services.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England has provided assurance that any prioritisation which is urgent on clinical grounds will continue to be dealt with quickly through their existing procedures. The route for individual funding requests remains in place.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The consultation can be found at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.engage.england.nhs.uk/consultation/investing-in-specialised-commissioning" target="_blank">www.engage.england.nhs.uk/consultation/investing-in-specialised-commissioning</a></p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-03-25T13:35:09.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228728/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228728/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-03-19","Rare Diseases","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that commissioning routes in respect of treatment for ultra-rare diseases are as quick and thorough as possible.","false","Biography information for Baroness Masham of Ilton",,"Baroness Masham of Ilton","HL5910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228729","Department of Health","false","2015-03-26","<p>The UK Strategy for Rare Diseases commits all four countries of the United Kingdom to work to achieve reduced times for diagnosis of rare diseases and to work with the National Health Service and clinicians to establish appropriate diagnostic pathways which are accessible to, and understood by, professionals and patients.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England commissions a highly specialised service for liver disease in children, including cirrhosis resulting from lysosomal acid lipase, from three expert centres in London, Birmingham and Leeds. These long established centres provide a clear referral pathway for expert diagnosis and management.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-03-26T12:51:28.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228729/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228729/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-03-19","Liver Diseases","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that people suffering from Lysosomal Acid Lipase Deficiency and other causes of cirrhosis in children are diagnosed as soon as possible and have a suitable route to commissioning that is as streamlined and effective as possible.","false","Biography information for Baroness Masham of Ilton",,"Baroness Masham of Ilton","HL5911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228730","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-03-26","<p>Foreign and Commonwealth Office officials regularly met civil society organisations and individual human rights defenders both in the UK and in Zimbabwe throughout 2014. They will continue to meet organisations on a regular basis to discuss and share views on the situation in Zimbabwe.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-03-26T12:56:24.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228730/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228730/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-03-19","Zimbabwe","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what meetings were held between the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and United Kingdom civil society organisations regarding Zimbabwe in 2014; and what further meetings they have planned.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL5912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228731","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-03-26","<p>There were no grants from the Human Rights and Democracy Programme (HRDP) for work in Zimbabwe in 2014-15. This reflects both the highly competitive nature of the global fund, and the extent to which the bids submitted in that period met the UK’s criteria.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-03-26T12:55:43.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228731/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228731/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-03-19","Zimbabwe","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many grants there were for support for work on Zimbabwe from the Human Rights and Democracy Fund in 2014–15.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL5913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228732","Home Office","false","2015-03-24","<p>The Government is considering the full implications of the judgment. Any proposals for changes to the designation of countries must be made by order, and will be put to Parliament. We will continue to consider each asylum and human rights claim on its own merits.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-03-24T14:58:55.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228732/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228732/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-03-19","Asylum: LGBT People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps will be taken to implement the Supreme Court’s recent judgment in R (JB (Jamaica)) v Secretary of State for the Home Department [2015] UKSC 8; and whether they intend to carry out a fundamental review of those countries designated under section 94(5) of the Nationality, Immigration and Asylum Act 2002, in the light of discrimination and violence experienced by LGBTI people in certain countries.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL5914"
