"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228192","Department of Health","false","2015-03-23","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The majority of trade unions that represent Agenda for Change staff recently agreed to accept the Government’s pay offer aimed at providing the most support to the lowest paid.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>From April 2015, pay for the lowest paid National Health Service staff will increase from £14,300 to £15,100 per annum. Those on the lowest pay point will receive an increase of 5.6% and staff on the second pay point an increase of 3.1%.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2015-03-23T17:10:52.743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228192/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228192/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228192/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-03-18","Health Services: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many staff are paid (a) above and (b) below the living wage by (i) Lancashire Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust and (ii) Lancashire Care NHS Foundation Trust.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mark Hendrick","228105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228193","Department of Health","false","2015-03-23","<p>Support and guidance to understand and comply with the automatic enrolment duties is provided by the Pensions Regulator (TPR). TPR recognises the particular challenges automatic enrolment raises for people who employ workers for their own care and support and has been working to ensure their communications and help meet the needs of this unique group of employers. TPR has available specific information and guidance for those that employ personal assistants and carers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Their contact centre staff have been trained to deal with the specific issues that might arise when an employer identifies themselves as an employer of a personal assistant or carer. TPR is reaching out to this group of employers through third party organisations to not only help them get automatic enrolment right, but to make it as simple as possible and is also working with local authorities and central government to make sure that the message is consistent and clear.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Further information is available at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.thepensionsregulator.gov.uk/docs/The_essential_guide_for_people_who_employ_their_own_care_and_support.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.thepensionsregulator.gov.uk/docs/The_essential_guide_for_people_who_employ_their_own_care_and_support.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","228097","2015-03-23T17:24:20.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228193/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228193/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228193/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-03-18","Carers: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what support is available to help people who lack capacity and who fund their own care, to set up and manage their contributions to their carers' workplace pensions.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","228096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228194","Department of Health","false","2015-03-25","<p>The Department’s Ministers have had no such discussions with University Hospitals of Leicester NHS Trust.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The commissioning and provision of National Health Services is a matter for the NHS locally.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-03-25T16:21:04.47Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228194/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228194/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228194/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-03-18","University Hospitals of Leicester NHS Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with University Hospitals of Leicester Trust on steps to ensure that patients with complex respiratory issues have access to specialist physiotherapy.","false","Biography information for Lord Garnier","Harborough","Sir Edward Garnier","228079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228195","Department of Health","false","2015-03-23","<p>Support and guidance to understand and comply with the automatic enrolment duties is provided by the Pensions Regulator (TPR). TPR recognises the particular challenges automatic enrolment raises for people who employ workers for their own care and support and has been working to ensure their communications and help meet the needs of this unique group of employers. TPR has available specific information and guidance for those that employ personal assistants and carers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Their contact centre staff have been trained to deal with the specific issues that might arise when an employer identifies themselves as an employer of a personal assistant or carer. TPR is reaching out to this group of employers through third party organisations to not only help them get automatic enrolment right, but to make it as simple as possible and is also working with local authorities and central government to make sure that the message is consistent and clear.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Further information is available at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.thepensionsregulator.gov.uk/docs/The_essential_guide_for_people_who_employ_their_own_care_and_support.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.thepensionsregulator.gov.uk/docs/The_essential_guide_for_people_who_employ_their_own_care_and_support.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","228096","2015-03-23T17:24:20.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228195/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228195/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228195/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-03-18","Carers: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what support is available to help people who fund their own care to enrol qualifying carers into a workplace pension.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","228097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228196","Department of Health","false","2015-03-25","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) is undertaking technology appraisals of several new drugs for the treatment of hepatitis C.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In advance of the NICE guidance, NHS England will be extending access to non-interferon based therapies for some patient groups with hepatitis C. Interferon remains a standard treatment recommended by NICE.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England has advised that it is not able to give an estimate of the number of patients who will commence treatment with these medicines in 2015 at this stage.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-03-25T12:49:57.043Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228196/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228196/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228196/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-03-18","Hepatitis: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department and NHS England are taking to accelerate the access of hepatitis C patient to interferon-free medicines; and what estimate he has made of the number of patients who will commence treatment with such medicines in 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","228063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228197","Department of Health","false","2015-03-25","<p>The commissioning and provision of National Health Services is a matter for the NHS locally.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2015-03-25T12:25:05.573Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228197/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228197/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228197/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-03-18","Nottingham University Hospitals NHS Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will discuss with Nottingham University Hospital Trust steps to ensure that patients have access to specialist physiotherapy.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","228064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228198","Department of Health","false","2015-03-25","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-03-25T14:28:12.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228198/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228198/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228198/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-03-18","Community First Responders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of Community First Responders supporting ambulance responses in (a) England, (b) the North West and (c) East Lancashire.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","228058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228199","Department of Health","false","2015-03-25","<p>There have been no such recent discussions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In England, the current clinical consensus is that low dose aspirin is not recommended purely for primary prevention of cardiovascular disease.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-03-25T12:09:17.57Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228199/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228199/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228199/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-03-18","Aspirin","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with the Royal Colleges and the British Medical Association about steps to reduce excessive usage of aspirin leading to internal bleeding or strokes.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","228017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228200","Department of Health","false","2015-03-25","<p>No assessment has been made of the number of people in each age group who have suffered from chronic fatigue syndrome in each of the last five years. With the exception of cancer, there is no comprehensive central record of disease diagnosis for any condition. In 2007 The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence produced the clinical guidance ‘<em>Chronic fatigue syndrome/myalgic encephalomyelitis (or encephalopathy): Diagnosis and management of CFS/ME in adults and children</em>’, which estimates that the annual prevalence is approximately 4,000 cases per million of the population.</p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2015-03-25T16:32:38.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228200/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228200/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228200/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-03-18","Chronic Fatigue Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of people in each age group who have suffered from chronic fatigue syndrome in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","228018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228201","Department of Health","false","2015-03-25","<p>Local National Health Service organisations are responsible for identifying and disposing of surplus estate. The Department collects annually information about NHS land that is surplus or potentially surplus to clinical requirements. An extract of this data, excluding sites that have been defined by the NHS as sensitive, is attached.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2015-03-25T12:35:53.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228201/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228201/answer","Surplus NHS Properties.xls","Surplus NHS Properties.xls","Surplus NHS properties","Surplus NHS properties","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228201/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-03-18","NHS: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which properties in the NHS estate his Department has identified as being surplus to requirements.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","228047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228202","Department of Health","false","2015-03-25","<p>The main provisions of the Health and Social Care Act 2012 came into effect on 1 April 2013. They reshaped the National Health Service so that is more patient-centred, led by health professionals and focussed on delivering world-class health outcomes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State announced the costs in his Written Ministerial Statement of 22 July 2014 official report, column 119WS.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These have been more than covered by the savings arising from the Health and Social Care Act which, up to 31 March 2014, were approximately £4.9 billion, and the NHS will see recurrent savings of £1.5 billion per year as a result of the reforms. This money will be available for reinvestment in future patient care.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2015-03-25T12:09:51.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228202/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228202/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-03-18","Health and Social Care Act 2012","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the cost has been of implementing the Health and Social Care Act 2012.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","228045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228203","Department of Health","false","2015-03-25","<p>Between 2010/11 and 2013/14 the Department and its non-departmental public bodies spent the following on vacant property:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>2010 - £500,669</p><p> </p><p>2011 - £352,875</p><p> </p><p>2012 - £163,996</p><p> </p><p>2013 - £229,540</p><p> </p><p>2014 - £174,669</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>This includes spend on holding costs such as maintenance and security, for wholly vacant properties.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2015-03-25T13:12:09.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228203/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228203/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-03-18","Empty Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much his Department and each of its non-departmental public bodies has spent on vacant properties since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","228046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228204","Home Office","false","2015-03-23","<p>Figures on the number of staff dedicated to dealing with domestic violence are not centrally held by the Home Office. <br><br>However, the Home Office does collect statistics on the number of police workers within the Child/Sex/Domestic/Missing function. Figures are only available at force level and cannot be broken down further. Data for 2015 have not yet been collected centrally and will not be available until the autumn. <br><br>The table provided shows the number of full-time equivalent police workers, by worker type, within the Child/Sex/Domestic/Missing function for Lancashire Constabulary, as at 31 March 2013 to 31 March 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2015-03-23T16:14:48.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228204/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228204/answer","PQ228087_table.xls","PQ228087_table.xls","Full-time equivalent policeworkers by type","Full-time equivalent policeworkers by type","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228204/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-03-18","Domestic Abuse: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many dedicated staff there were at each rank dealing with domestic violence at each police station in Lancashire in (a) 2013, (b) 2014 and (c) 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mark Hendrick","228087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228205","Cabinet Office","false","2015-03-25","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2015-03-25T10:54:08.72Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228205/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228205/answer","PQ 228082 ONS 113.pdf","PQ 228082 ONS 113.pdf","ONS Letter to Member - Shoplifting and Theft","ONS Letter to Member - Shoplifting and Theft","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228205/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-03-18","Shoplifting: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many incidents of shoplifting and theft from shops were reported to police in (a) Preston constituency, (b) Lancashire and (c) the North West in (i) 2010, (ii) 2011, (iii) 2012, (iv) 2013 and (v) 2014.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mark Hendrick","228082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228206","Home Office","false","2015-03-24","<p>Her Majesty's Government issued a Country Policy Bulletin on the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) in October 2014 which includes guidance and country information for asylum decision-makers on considering the risks faced by womenreturning to the DRC. <br><br>The Bulletin is available at: <br><br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/democratic-republic-of-congo-country-information-and-guidance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/democratic-republic-of-congo-country-information-and-guidance</a> <br><br>The Bulletin cites the Freedom from Torture (FfT) report of June 2014 and a July 2013 FfT submission to the UN Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women on the same subject.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-03-24T15:26:21.47Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228206/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228206/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-03-18","Rape: Democratic Republic of Congo","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department has taken to implement the recommendations in the report, Rape as torture in the DRC, published by Freedom from Torture in June 2014.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","228160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228207","Home Office","false","2015-03-24","<p>Police pensions are funded by each police force paying employer and officer contributions into a separate account. These funds are then used to pay current police pensions.<br><br>Where the income into the police force’s pensions account is not sufficient to meet the cash cost of pensions being paid to retired officers, this is topped up by Home Office grant. <br><br>A breakdown across all forces is not available immediately. However, in total* the Home Office has provided the following top-up funding as follows:<br><br>• 2006/07 - £291million<br>• 2007/08 - £352million<br>• 2008/09 - £630million<br>• 2009/10 - £639 million<br>• 2010/11 - £721 million<br>• 2011/12 - £1,064 million<br>• 2012/13 - £1,218 million<br>• 2013/14 - £1,291million**<br>• 2014/15 - £1,441million***<br><br>* The total figure includes funding for all 43 forces in England and Wales as well as other bodies such as Her Majesty's Inspectorate of Constabulary.<br><br>** The figure for 2013/14 is based on police authorities' unaudited data only at this stage, and payment of the balance in respect of 2013/14 is yet to be made; the figure provided is the total expected grant requirement once the balance of payment in arrears has been made.<br><br>*** Forecast</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-03-24T15:24:56.65Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228207/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228207/answer","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228207/answer/previousversion/51782","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-03-18","Police: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what funding her Department provided in police pension top-up grants to each police force in England and Wales in each year since 2006-07.","false","Biography information for Mr Stewart Jackson","Peterborough","Mr Stewart Jackson","228167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228208","Home Office","false","2015-03-24","<p>The table provided contains data on the number of full-time police officers (headcount) employed by Merseyside Police as at 31 March 2010 to 31 March 2014. <br>Over this period, full-time police officers have fallen by 595 police officers or 14%. <br><br>Over the same period, police recorded crime (excluding fraud) has fallen by 13%in Merseyside police force area.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><strong>Number of full-time police officers (headcount<sup>1</sup>) employed by Merseyside Police as at 31 March 2010 to 31 March 2014<sup>2</sup></strong></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td>2010</td><td>2011</td><td>2012</td><td>2013</td><td>2014</td><td> </td></tr><tr><td>Merseyside Police</td><td>4,399</td><td>4,173</td><td>3,962</td><td>3,769</td><td>3,804</td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="6">1. These figures are provided on a headcount basis, they represent total officers (headcount) less part-time officers (headcount).</td><td> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="6">2. Police officer numbers as at 31 March 2014 with full-time/part-time breakdowns, by police force area, are published in the Police Workforce, England and Wales, 31 March 2014 statistical publication and can be found at: https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-workforce-england-and-wales. Previously only the total number of police officers was published without a full-time/part-time split in the published tables. They have not been verified by police forces and are provisional.</td><td> </td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-03-24T15:24:11.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228208/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/228208/answer",,,,,"http